President Barack Obama has proclaimed November 2016 as National Native American Heritage Month. In his proclamation, he recognizes the contributions Native Americans have made to the United States and acknowledges the challenges and injustices they have faced throughout history. The President emphasizes his Administration's commitment to strengthening government-to-government relationships with tribal nations and improving the lives of all Native Americans. He mentions various initiatives and policies aimed at supporting Native American communities, including the establishment of the White House Council on Native American Affairs, the protection of sacred lands, the promotion of tribal sovereignty in criminal justice matters, and the expansion of access to quality healthcare. Additionally, the President highlights efforts to expand educational opportunities, job training, clean-energy projects, infrastructure, and high-speed internet in Indian Country. He calls on all Americans to celebrate Native American heritage and commemorate Native American Heritage Day on November 25, 2016.